Read in 1B data

options(scipen=999) # remove scientific notation

data1B <- read_csv(here("data_files", "scored_master_dataset_1B.csv"))

Select only relevant 1B data

data1Bselect <- data1B %>%
  select(article_id_number, subfield, total_data_score, total_materials_score)

Read in 1A data

data1A <- read_csv(here("data_files", "scored_master_dataset_1A.csv"))

Select only relevant 1A data

data1Aselect <- data1A %>%
  select(article_id_number, subfield, total_data_score, total_materials_score)

Merge 1A and 1B data into one dataframe

alldata <- rbind(data1Aselect, data1Bselect)

First factor: Subfield

# let's let's collapse the subfields into 4 main groups: developmental, cognition, social and 'other'
subfield_groups <- alldata %>%
  mutate(subfield_groups = case_when(subfield == "Behavioural Neuroscience" ~ "Other",
                                     subfield == "Cognitive Neuroscience" ~ "Other",
                                     subfield == "Health Psychology" ~ "Other",
                                     subfield == "Perception" ~ "Other",
                                     subfield == "Developmental Psychology" ~ "Development",
                                     subfield == "Social Psychology" ~  "Social",
                                     TRUE ~ as.character(subfield))) %>%
  relocate(subfield_groups, .after = subfield)

# we can now delete the original subfield column
subfield_groups <- subfield_groups %>%
  select(-subfield)

Second factor: Time period

dates <- subfield_groups %>%
  mutate(time_period = case_when(
    str_detect(article_id_number, "1-2014|2-2014|3-2014|4-2014|5-2014|6-2014") ~ "1st half 2014",
    str_detect(article_id_number, "7-2014|8-2014|9-2014|10-2014|11-2014|12-2014") ~ "2nd half 2014",
    str_detect(article_id_number, "1-2015|2-2015|3-2015|4-2015|5-2015") ~ "1st half 2015",
    str_detect(article_id_number, "2019-30-7|2019-30-8|2019-30-9|2019-30-10|2019-30-11|2019-30-12") ~ "2nd half 2019",
    str_detect(article_id_number, "2020-31-1|2020-31-2|2020-31-3|2020-31-4|2020-31-5|2020-31-6") ~ "1st half 2020",
    str_detect(article_id_number, "2020-31-7|2020-31-8|2020-31-9|2020-31-10|2020-31-11|2020-31-12") ~ "2nd half 2020")) %>%
  relocate(time_period, .after = article_id_number)

# make sure subfield and timeperiod are factors 

dates$subfield_groups <- as.factor(dates$subfield_groups)
dates$time_period <- fct_relevel(dates$time_period, c("1st half 2014", "2nd half 2014", "1st half 2015", "2nd half 2019", "1st half 2020","2nd half 2020"))

levels(dates$time_period)
## [1] "1st half 2014" "2nd half 2014" "1st half 2015" "2nd half 2019"
## [5] "1st half 2020" "2nd half 2020"

DATA ANOVA

data_ANOVA <- dates %>%
  anova_test(total_data_score ~ subfield_groups * time_period)
## Coefficient covariances computed by hccm()
data_ANOVA
## ANOVA Table (type II tests)
## 
##                        Effect DFn DFd      F
## 1             subfield_groups   3 491  3.671
## 2                 time_period   5 491 53.217
## 3 subfield_groups:time_period  15 491  1.617
##                                                  p p<.05   ges
## 1 0.0120000000000000002498001805406602215953171253     * 0.022
## 2 0.0000000000000000000000000000000000000000000416     * 0.351
## 3 0.0650000000000000022204460492503130808472633362       0.047

Our two-way between-subjects ANOVA generated a significant main effect of subfield, F(3, 491) = 3.671, p = 0.012, ges = 0.022, and time period, F(5, 491) = 53.217, p = 0, ges = 0.351. However, the interaction between subfield and time period, F(15, 491) = 1.617, ges = 0.047, was not statistically significant.

# Alternatively we can use the papaja package to print the stats: 

data_aov <- aov_ez(
  data = dates, dv = "total_data_score", 
  id = "article_id_number", 
  between = c("time_period", "subfield_groups"), 
  type = "2"
)
## Contrasts set to contr.sum for the following variables: time_period, subfield_groups
data_aov$anova_table
## Anova Table (Type 2 tests)
## 
## Response: total_data_score
##                             num Df den Df    MSE       F     ges
## time_period                      5    491 52.389 53.2174 0.35146
## subfield_groups                  3    491 52.389  3.6709 0.02194
## time_period:subfield_groups     15    491 52.389  1.6167 0.04707
##                                           Pr(>F)    
## time_period                 < 0.0000000000000002 ***
## subfield_groups                          0.01227 *  
## time_period:subfield_groups              0.06540 .  
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
data_apa <- apa_print(data_aov)

apa_table(data_apa$table,
          caption = "Between-subjects ANOVA for Open Data Scores", 
          note = "This table was created with apa_table().")
(#tab:unnamed-chunk-10)
Between-subjects ANOVA for Open Data Scores
Effect \(F\) \(\mathit{df}_1\) \(\mathit{df}_2\) \(\mathit{MSE}\) \(p\) \(\hat{\eta}^2_G\)
Time period 53.22 5 491 52.39 < .001 .351
Subfield groups 3.67 3 491 52.39 .012 .022
Time period \(\times\) Subfield groups 1.62 15 491 52.39 .065 .047

Note. This table was created with apa_table().

Our two-way between-subjects ANOVA generated a significant main effect of time period, \(F(5, 491) = 53.22\), \(\mathit{MSE} = 52.39\), \(p < .001\), \(\hat{\eta}^2_G = .351\), and a significant main effect of subfield, \(F(3, 491) = 3.67\), \(\mathit{MSE} = 52.39\), \(p = .012\), \(\hat{\eta}^2_G = .022\). However, the interaction between time period and subfield, \(F(15, 491) = 1.62\), \(\mathit{MSE} = 52.39\), \(p = .065\), \(\hat{\eta}^2_G = .047\), was not statistically significant.

PLOTS

DATA

Subfield x Data Score

data_subfield_descriptives <- dates %>%
  group_by(subfield_groups) %>%
  summarise(mean_data_score = mean(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            SD = sd(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            N = n(),
            stderr = SD/sqrt(N))

# let's plot this

data_subfield_descriptives %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = reorder(subfield_groups, mean_data_score), y = mean_data_score, fill = subfield_groups)) +
  geom_col() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_data_score - stderr, ymax = mean_data_score + stderr), # specifying what the standard error is
                size=.3, # thinner lines
                width=.2) + # narrower bars
  theme_classic() + # white background
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,25), expand = c(0,0)) + # getting the bars to start at the bottom of the graph
  easy_remove_legend() +
  easy_all_text_size(size = 9) + # change the size of the text
  easy_labs(x = "Subfield", y = "Mean Open Data Score") + # change the x and y labels
  theme(plot.margin=unit(c(1,1,1,1),"cm")) # more white space

Time Period x Data Score

data_timeperiod_descriptives <- dates %>%
  group_by(time_period) %>%
  summarise(mean_data_score = mean(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            SD = sd(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            N = n(),
            stderr = SD/sqrt(N))

# let's plot this

  ggplot(aes(x = time_period, y = mean_data_score, fill = time_period)) +
  geom_col() +

  theme_classic() + # white background
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,21), expand = c(0,0)) + # getting the bars to start at the bottom of the graph
  easy_remove_legend() +

  easy_labs(x = "Time Period", y = "Mean Open Data Score") + # change the x and y labels
  theme(plot.margin=unit(c(1,1,1,1),"cm")) # more white space

Interaction between time and subfield - Data scores

data_subfieldtime_descriptives <- dates %>%
  group_by(subfield_groups, time_period) %>%
  summarise(mean_data_score = mean(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            SD = sd(total_data_score, na.rm = TRUE),
            N = n(),
            stderr = SD/sqrt(N))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'subfield_groups'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.
data_subfieldtime_descriptives  %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = subfield_groups, y = mean_data_score, fill = time_period)) +
  geom_col(position = "dodge") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = mean_data_score - stderr, ymax = mean_data_score + stderr), # specifying what the standard error is
                size=.3, # thinner lines
                width=.2, # narrower bars
                position=position_dodge(.9)) + 
  theme_classic() + # white background
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,25), expand = c(0,0)) + # getting the bars to start at the bottom of the graph
  easy_all_text_size(size = 9) + # change the size of the text
  easy_labs(x = "Subfield", y = "Mean Open Data Score") + # change the x and y labels
  theme(plot.margin=unit(c(1,1,1,1),"cm"))  # more white space

SUBFIELD T-TESTS

DATA

Development vs.Cognition

devcog_data <- dates %>%
  filter(subfield_groups %in% c("Development", "Cognition"))

pairwise_t_test(devcog_data, total_data_score ~ subfield_groups)
## # A tibble: 1  9
##   .y.              group1    group2    n1    n2       p p.signif   p.adj p.adj.signif
## * <chr>            <chr>     <chr>  <int> <int>   <dbl> <chr>      <dbl> <chr>       
## 1 total_data_score Cognition Devel   152    99 0.00442 **       0.00442 **
devcog_data_output <- apa_print(t.test(total_data_score ~ subfield_groups, data = devcog_data))

A pairwise t-test showed that articles published in the subfield of Cognition generated significantly higher average Open Data Scores than articles in Developmental Psychology, \(t(226.91) = 2.95\), \(p = .004\).

Development vs.Social

devsocial_data <- dates %>%
  filter(subfield_groups %in% c("Development", "Social"))

pairwise_t_test(devsocial_data, total_data_score ~ subfield_groups)
## # A tibble: 1  9
##   .y.              group1      group2    n1    n2      p p.signif  p.adj p.adj.signif
## * <chr>            <chr>       <chr>  <int> <int>  <dbl> <chr>     <dbl> <chr>       
## 1 total_data_score Development Social    99   148 0.0811 ns       0.0811 ns
devsocial_data_output <- apa_print(t.test(total_data_score ~ subfield_groups, data = devsocial_data))

A pairwise t-test showed that articles published in the subfield of Social Psychology did not generate significantly different Open Data Scores, on average, than articles in Developmental Psychology, \(t(218.67) = -1.77\), \(p = .078\).
